      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Ansys Mechanical and in-house FDA FEA code operate under documented software quality management plans; version control and regression test suites in place.",
      "rationale": "All three modeling environments (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) maintain version-controlled codebases with documented SQA procedures. Regression test suites covering linear-elastic structural elements were executed prior to the study. Achieved level equals required level for Medium model risk."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems (NAFEMS standard cases) demonstrate element formulations reproduce analytical solutions to within 1% for beam-bending and contact problems relevant to the pedicle screw geometry.",
      "rationale": "NAFEMS benchmark LE1 and LE10 cases were run in each solver. Maximum deviation from analytical solutions was 0.7%. Code verification is judged sufficient for a linear-elastic, small-displacement regime applicable to the F1717 test."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates QoI change of less than 2% between medium and fine mesh densities across all three QoIs.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study (coarse, medium, fine) was conducted. Stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement changed by less than 1.4% between medium and fine meshes. Richardson extrapolation-based GCI values were below 2% for all QoIs. Discretization error is adequately controlled."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals converge below 1e-6 relative tolerance; direct solver used for final production runs to eliminate iterative convergence uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "A direct sparse solver (PARDISO) was used for all production analyses, eliminating iterative convergence error. Residual force norms at each load step were below 1e-8. Achieved level exceeds the required level of 1 for this factor."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup, boundary conditions, and material assignments completed by a second analyst not involved in original model construction.",
      "rationale": "An independent analyst reviewed boundary condition application, contact pair definitions, and material property assignments against the ASTM F1717 fixture geometry. No discrepancies were identified. Modeling workflow is documented in a formal simulation plan traceable to the study protocol."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Linear-elastic isotropic material model and small-displacement assumption are justified for the pre-yield loading regime; plasticity model validated against coupon tensile data for post-yield regime.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V material behavior in the pre-yield regime is well-characterized as linear-elastic; the assumption is consistent with ASTM F1717 stiffness measurement protocol. A bilinear isotropic hardening model was applied for post-yield prediction of yield force and 40 mm displacement force, calibrated against tensile coupon data from the same material lot. Model form uncertainty is quantified and within acceptable bounds."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties (E, yield strength, UTS, tangent modulus) sourced from lot-specific coupon testing; geometric dimensions from CMM measurements of production screws used in bench tests.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus, yield strength, and post-yield tangent modulus were measured from five tensile coupons machined from the same Ti-6Al-4V bar stock used to manufacture the test screws. CMM measurements of rod diameter, screw shank diameter, and UHMWPE block geometry were used to define FEA geometry. Input uncertainty propagation confirmed QoI sensitivity to material scatter is less than 3%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N=11 constructs tested across two independent laboratories; constructs assembled from production-representative screws and rods with documented dimensional inspection.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were assembled and tested, distributed across two independent test laboratories. All components were drawn from a single production lot with CMM-verified dimensions. Inter-laboratory variability in QoIs was within 4%, confirming sample representativeness."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions replicate in vivo loading environment across a range of clinically relevant load magnitudes and fixture configurations.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted at a single ASTM F1717 fixture configuration (10-degree lordotic angle) and a single crosshead displacement rate. While ASTM F1717 is the accepted regulatory standard, only one test condition was evaluated, limiting coverage of the clinical loading envelope. Achieved level (2) is below the required level (3); this gap is acknowledged and accepted given the regulatory precedent of F1717 as the definitive bench test for pedicle screw constructs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA model inputs (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions) are demonstrably equivalent to the physical test configuration used in the validation experiments.",
      "rationale": "FEA geometry was constructed directly from CMM measurements of the tested constructs. Boundary conditions replicate the F1717 fixture constraints as confirmed by fixture engineering drawings. Material properties are lot-matched to tested hardware. Equivalency between simulation inputs and experimental conditions is fully documented."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) satisfy both the <10% relative difference criterion and the E/uval < 1.96 validation metric.",
      "rationale": "Stiffness: FEA mean within 4.2% of experimental mean, E/uval = 0.87. Yield force: FEA within 6.8%, E/uval = 1.41. Force at 40 mm: FEA within 5.1%, E/uval = 1.03. All three QoIs satisfy both acceptance criteria. Output comparison is judged fully adequate."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Selected QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are mechanistically linked to clinical failure modes (fatigue crack initiation, construct loosening) and are accepted regulatory endpoints for pedicle screw submissions.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness governs load transfer to adjacent vertebrae and is linked to adjacent segment disease risk. Yield force and force at 40 mm displacement are directly correlated with fatigue life and are standard FDA-accepted endpoints for 510(k) pedicle screw submissions. QoI relevance to the COU is high."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments replicate the device geometry, material, loading mode, and regulatory test standard applicable to the intended COU.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity uses production-representative non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screws tested under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending, which is the identical test modality the FEA model is intended to support in the regulatory submission. The validation activity is directly relevant to the COU with no significant gap in device geometry, loading mode, or regulatory context."
    }
